segments.text: Okay, you were giving impressions of Dr. Calhoun.
My relationship with him started in the early 60s, and the Department of Commerce,
when I was a guest at the Department of Commerce, started what they called an Office of Technical Services,
and what they would do is they would provide you funding to answer inquiries from industry in your state.
So Dr. Calhoun created at that time what he called the State Technical Services Institute.
He asked me to serve as director of that, which I did.
And so I had some connection with him, but the real connection, I guess,
comes with the Sea Grant Program that I had there.
I had quite a hunk of that Sea Grant Program at one time,
and that came down there in the late 60s as well, so it had to be from 6 to 3.
And I did a lot of work with the Sea Grant Program.
I used my industrial economics staff, it was perfect.
It would be all economic studies along the cone, things of that nature.
And... OTS had gone out of business, by the way,
Office of Technical Services had gone out of business,
so then I got in on the Sea Grant Program,
and of course we run all those things.
So that's really the period between 65 and 73 is when I got really close.
Make believe that I had never seen John Calhoun.
Describe him physically and his style.
I wish I had a picture, I could just give it to you.
Dr. Calhoun was probably the most diversified, intelligent individual that I had.
Dr. Calhoun could grasp things rapidly.
He did a lot of reading on these things before I come in contact with him or not,
but I mean, he was always very well versed.
My experience with him was through the State Technical Services Sea Grant Program.
He was a very easy person to talk to.
I never had seen Dr. Calhoun.
Now some people have seen Dr. Calhoun mad, I've never seen him mad.
Never had in my life.
We attended a lot of conferences together.
I did a lot of studies.
Then one day out of the clear blue sky in 1973,
on a Thursday afternoon, I was working away,
and I got this phone call from Dr. Williams.
And Dr. Williams said,
Jim, I believe I told you before, I was having my industrial conference start Monday,
and I had the governor coming over to get the welcome to press,
which I had every year.
And Dr. Williams said, Jim, I'd like to tell you this.
In a few minutes, we were going to do this.
I said, well, I'd love to.
He said, fine.
I went down to his office.
And after about five minutes of shaking hands and things, he said,
you know, we have a vacancy as director of the Indian Education Service,
and we want to create an Office of the Indian Education.
And he said, I'd like for you to head to his office.
Now, tell me about this man, Jack Williams.
Well, of course, Jack Williams and Dr. Calhoun were very close, business-wise.
I don't know if that's working or not.
But they were always there.
They had a lot of respect for each other.
So I said, well, Dr. Williams, I don't know.
I didn't even know there was a vacancy.
I had the job, but I really enjoyed it.
It was getting bigger every day.
It was getting more statewide and that, the recognition.
I said, I'd have to think about it a little bit.
He said, well, do you need anything to think about?
I said, yes.
I said, I want a copy of the budget.
I said, I want to see what kind of budget they have,
all the sources of money that's coming to us.
So he got on the phone, and he called Fred Benson,
if I'm not mistaken.
It might have been Calhoun, but he called somebody
and told them to get him back in.
I'd like you to get some budgets up here for the
Engineering Extension Service.
And so he got them.
How did that happen?
And so we just did a few minutes.
He said, well, when do you think we can get back together?
I said, we'll get back together Monday morning.
I have all Saturday and Sunday.
We'll get back Monday morning.
So he said, well, just give me a ring Monday morning,
and then we're ready.
So we just kept it that way.
I didn't get to talk to him until about 3 o'clock that afternoon.
But I went there, and I told him what my problem was.
And I had, you know, if I didn't do anything,
you know, if I want to do this, I need this.
I need this.
I need this.
I need this.
I need this, this, this.
Got down to the bottom line.
The most important thing, I had to have total control
of all the people in the organization.
And if I was going to be fair with them,
I was going to be bad with each one of them.
But if they didn't fit into the organization,
if I was going to plan for this,
I was going to have to find somebody
who would feel like the problem.
But anyway, it went on like that.
And I had to listen pretty long.
He said, is that all?
I said, yes, sir.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing.
He said, no, I think he said, you haven't asked for nothing.
You can't get it.
And so I said, OK.
So then he called Fred Benson in Calhoun
and told him that I'd accepted the job.
I guess Calhoun could tell you more about it from now on.
As far as you know, he had talked with each of them
Oh, yes.
Oh, I'm quite sure of that.
I mean, Pastor Williams would have done...
No.
And another thing I had,
see, I had a lot of research projects in that industry,
in industrial and electrical research.
And this was in August when he called me in.
And I told him, I said,
I couldn't possibly accept the job
until he sent the firm.
Because I had sponsors out here
that supported me for years.
And I said, well, that'd be fun.
That didn't bother him any.
Describe the extension service when you took over.
What was it?
How big was it?
Well, it was in the old American Legion Hall.
Bob Weitz was before he moved out there.
That used to be the...
Do you remember that?
Or was it already down when you got here?
I don't know.
I was here...
Do you remember where the headquarters for Bob Weitz was
up until just about a year ago?
No, I don't.
Well, you know where the
Farmer Student Association building is now?
It used to be that old wooden building right across the street.
Oh, across the street.
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.
Over there by the police station.
Yeah.
Well, I didn't know anybody.
I didn't know anybody in any of this except Ernie Winochek.
The only reason I knew him, he had lost some of my age.
And I had met him through Buddy Williams.
He and Ernie were pretty good friends.
But he's the only one I knew.
And so when I took over, they took action at the October 4th.
We made the motion.
Ms. Wilson seconded it.
This is 73.
Yeah, 73.
I forgot to go over.
He said before 73.
Okay.
I forgot to go over.
I forgot to go over.
I forgot to go over.
I forgot to go over.
But this meeting was in October before the meeting.
And so when that was announced and it came out in the paper and everything, by the day,
well, by the way, not tonight, you know, the dean was approved the same day I was approved
to direct the Engineering Extension Service.
His pitch is on the front page of the evening on one side and mine is on the other.
And I just saw where they pitched that monument or whatever it was.
But when I went over to the Engineering Extension Service, it had a budget of about $1.5 million
and they had about $50 million.
Where were they based?
I don't know.
I mean, you know, they were all in the Department of Engineering.
They were all in the Department of Engineering.
It had a budget of about $1.5 million and they had about $50 million.
Where were they based?
All of them here?
Yeah.
Okay.
At that time.
They were a very, they weren't up-to-date.
There was not an area that you could find that was taught without lesson plans, that
they didn't have any technical manuals.
It's a training organization.
But they had 51 employees and about, but their budget come, one-third come from Texas
Education Agency, one-third come directly from Appropriations, and then they got one-third
of their budget from the city.
Well, you've got to realize, the Engineering Extension Service was an oval organization.
Most of the employees were, been there, you know, for a job.
Okay.
But anyway, when it was announced, they had Dr. Mansfield, and Deb was his final person,
but he had been let to lead either through himself or through Mr. Bearden.
See, Mr. Bearden had been director and he retired.
That he was going to be the director.
Well, by the way, when I become director, but anyway.
And all of them, the first day after COVID, December the 1st, 1973, I stayed away from
it until I went in for a third religious conference.
Well, after the first one, you know, I was in the room with them.
surgery.
She was operated on that morning, the first day I had to go.
Two important events.
Very important events.
I stayed with my wife.
I was Dr. Calhoun, which I don't know what I called her.
But anyway, they knew where I was at.
I stayed with her
and that was her third surgery.
So after they got
through with the surgery, it was in about five hours, the doctor
sent her down to Houston and started taking chemotherapy.
Anyway, after the third operation, my wife had about all the operations she wanted.
But anyway, they made an appointment for me to go see this doctor down in Houston.
And I got away at the appointment at 1.30 in the afternoon with my wife
and I walked in and I checked her in and she shut the door.
I stayed outside.
In about 20 minutes, or 15 minutes, he came out
and said, I'm sorry.
He said, your wife won't let me take you.
She said, she's not going to take you from up there.
He said, unless I get the exam.
I said, don't press that.
I said, are you sure you made up your mind?
He said, yup.
I said, how much did I owe him?
He said, $35.
I wrote him a check.
And that was in 1973.
Where did, primarily geographically, where did,
when you took over, where were they doing the instruction that they were?
They were going out in motels.
No, but where was it?
Was it in the Houston area?
Oh, it was all over the state.
But it wasn't common?
It wasn't concentrated in one?
No, no.
See, they were doing all the training
for rural electric co-ops.
They did lineman training and things of this nature.
They did a lot of training for the Texas Telephone Association.
See, they were getting subsidized.
Right.
Give more examples of that.
Okay, law enforcement.
Water and wastewater.
Fireman Training Center was all part of that?
Oh, yeah.
But they used volunteer instructors.
They only had four people.
Was there a client that was by far the key one, the biggest?
Well, your rural electric co-op, of course,
the organization was so small,
they only had,
how do I put this thing into perspective?
Now wait, give me those numbers again.
When I took over,
it was around 51, I think, employees.
We had a $39 million budget.
And of that budget,
how much did you offer?
Ten percent.
We got three million and something.
The rest you brought in.
When you started out,
you were primarily serving
small town needs,
and the telephone companies
were the co-ops.
The rural telephone companies.
Alright, let's see.
When you took over,
were there any key
office staff members
that you came to rely on?
I'm talking about
the people in the office.
I told you Dr. Matthews was a fine person.
He must have been a shock to his sister.
He had a different philosophy.
His philosophy and my philosophy
was completely 100% different.
I was used to the soft money operations.
I've always had the soft money.
They didn't like it.
Another thing I asked Dr. Williams,
I never did go down to that,
but I was up on the eighth floor.
When you took over,
in terms of reporting,
you reported to?
Dr. Calhoun.
In which order?
Was it to
Benson or was it to both
on paper?
Both of them.
I got funding from
Indian Education.
Alright, let's go back and talk about this man,
Benson.
He's a Kansan,
I think.
Tell me
about his working
style and so forth.
He never did leave.
He walked up.
He said, Mr. Benson,
I hear about so and so's.
We have our ground rules.
I set my ground rules with him.
He told me to inform you of something.
Give me some guidelines
because I don't have time
to tell you everything I do
and you don't have time
to listen to everything I do.
Give me your guidelines.
You know what Mr. Benson's answer was?
Keep me informed
that the Extension,
the Extension, Engineering Extension Service
was part of the
Texas A&M University
and of the system.
No, the Engineering Extension Service
was always a part of the system.
Alright.
During those
years with Williams and Calhoun and Benson,
did it matter,
system or campus?
Did it matter?
And how you operated?
It didn't matter
exactly what the system was supposed to do.
I knew the policies and procedures of the system
and I knew what the university was supposed to do
and I knew exactly what I was expected of in the university
and I knew exactly what I was expected in the institution.
When you wanted to communicate with them,
whom did you have to go through
to get to Calhoun or to Benson?
Nobody except their secretary.
They all, you always,
he had the same,
they had the same thing with me.
Alright.
As you think back on those
first years, what were some key decisions
that were made by you or anybody else?
Pertaining to the system?
Or pertaining to the work of the
of the Extension,
of the Extension, of the...
Engineering Extension Service?
Well, I'm not being derogatory,
but I make the role.
I had, you know,
the rest of them was all known to me.
They had one title.
It was all called...
My first thing that I did when I went in there
by January the first, I had a
I even, I had no pay range.
Everybody made the same.
So the first thing we did,
we gave them something to,
and then in February that year,
I had a meeting in Wyandale
to give them a copy of what I call
Management by Objective.
How we were going to run the Engineering Extension Service
and what part they were going to play.
But anyway, there was a few,
you've got to remember,
this was an old organization.
They'd all been in together.
Here's a damn stranger.
But anyway, after we had that meeting,
none of them understood management at all.
So we put that thing together.
I come into the recommendation
with Dr. Williams,
they had about,
I'd say they had about $500,000.
We'd automatically, if they had the qualifications,
they'd go into this pay status.
We'd give them each title,
training specialist.
That's how the decisions were made.
And then once we got that thing in line,
then unfortunately, poor old Gotham fans,
but he didn't buy that, sir.
So we had to take that out.
And then I brought in a new man
as associate director.
Right off.
He was a young engineer.
How do you spell his last name?
Ratke, R-A-T-K.
He was a TTI.
And how'd he come about being a TTI
getting into public work training?
Well, I had created a center for public work.
And I picked up the paper one Saturday morning
there was a TTI announcing
a public work training.
So I got ahold of Fred.
I said, I'll take care of that Monday morning.
We had Jack Keese in.
And all of a sudden,
he'd get out of public work.
That's an extension activity.
That's not a research activity.
And so Milton Ratke
was in that position.
We transferred him and one other TTI staff member.
And it turned out
that Milton was a very,
he's a very good engineer
and a very smart individual
and a very, very good writer.
So I brought him on as associate director.
And he's there every year.
You know, I've served him for a time.
But that's how that got started.
But when you have to have a decision made,
it took me
less than five minutes to get it.
I could call Benson.
He'd say, well, what did you do?
Or what do you want to do?
Or I could call Calhoun.
Calhoun wasn't as quick on the draw
as Benson was.
But he was still very quick.
You know what I mean?
I mean, I'd have more conversation with Calhoun
if I didn't get the impression
that either one of them ever made a snap judgment
without thinking it through.
I'm sure there are quite a few of us.
I think everybody that's done that.
Let's see.
Back to other decisions.
Because you're in charge for 19 years.
Other decisions that you now look back on
and say, those were key decisions we made.
Well, one key decision we made,
we had a reputation
in all of the states.
I could contact every legislator
with one phone call.
So I said, that's our fate.
So the first thing I did,
I put about $150,000 in that park.

I put that right on.

just east of Easterwood Airport.
Right.

But I had a man in electronics.

the problem was with them.

F-I-T-E.

on electronics.

training.

South Central Region Training Center,
